\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Frequency Bias
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "FBIAS" in CTS output (Table 4-5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Frequency Bias is the ratio of the total number of forecasts of an event
 to the total number of observations of the event.
 It is defined as
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{Bias}={{n_{11}+n_{10}}
\backslash
over {n_{11}+n_{01}}}={{n_{1.}}
\backslash
over {n_1}}.$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
A "good" value of Frequency Bias is close to 1; a value greater than 1 indicates
 the event was forecasted too frequently and a value less than 1 indicates
 the event was not forecasted frequently enough.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Probability of Detection (POD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "H_RATE" in FHO output (Table 4-3); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "PODY" in CTS output (Table 4-5) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
POD is defined as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{POD}={{n_{11}
\backslash
over{n_{11}+n_{01}}}}={n_{11}
\backslash
over{n_{1}}}.$$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
It is the fraction of events that were correctly forecasted to occur.
 POD is equivalent to the H value computed by the NCEP verification system
 and is also known as the hit rate.
 POD ranges from 0 to 1; a perfect forecast would have POD = 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Probability of False Detection (POFD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "POFD" in CTS output (Table 4-5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
POFD is defined as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{POFD}={{n_{10}
\backslash
over{n_{10}+n_{00}}}}={n_{10}
\backslash
over{n_{.0}}}.$$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
It is the proportion of non-events that were forecast to be events.
 POFD is also often called the False Alarm Rate.
 POFD ranges from 0 to 1; a perfect forecast would have POFD = 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Probability of Detection of the non-event (PODn)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "PODN" in CTS output (Table 4-5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
PODn is defined as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{PODN}={{n_{00}
\backslash
over{n_{10}+n_{00}}}}={n_{00}
\backslash
over{n_{.0}}}.$$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
It is the proportion of non-events that were correctly forecasted to be
 non-events.
 Note that PODn = 1 - POFD.
 PODn ranges from 0 to 1.
 Like POD, a perfect forecast would have PODn = 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
False Alarm Ratio (FAR)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "FAR" in CTS output (Table 4-5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
FAR is defined as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{FAR}={{n_{10}
\backslash
over{n_{10}+n_{11}}}}={n_{10}
\backslash
over{n_{1.}}}.$$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
It is the proportion of forecasts of the event occurring for which the event
 did not occur.
 FAR ranges from 0 to 1; a perfect forecast would have FAR = 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Critical Success Index (CSI)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "CSI" in CTS output (Table 4-5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
CSI is defined as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{CSI}={{n_{11}
\backslash
over{n_{11}+n_{10}+n_{01}}}}.$$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
It is the ratio of the number of times the event was correctly forecasted
 to occur to the number of times it was either forecasted or occurred.
 CSI ignores the "correct rejections" category (i.e., 
\series bold
n
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
00
\end_layout

\end_inset


\series default
).
 CSI is also known as the Threat Score (TS).
 CSI can also be written as a nonlinear combination of POD and FAR, and
 is strongly related to Frequency Bias and the Base Rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Gilbert Skill Score (GSS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "GSS" in CTS output (Table 4-5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
GSS is based on the CSI, corrected for the number of hits that would be
 expected by chance.
 In particular,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{GSS}=
\backslash
displaystyle{{{n_{11}-C_1}
\backslash
over{n_{11}+n_{10}+n_{01}-C_1}}},$$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$C=
\backslash
displaystyle{{(n_{11}+n_{10})(n_{11}+n_{01})}
\backslash
over{T}}.$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
GSS is also known as the Equitable Threat Score (ETS).
 GSS values range from -1/3 to 1.
 A no-skill forecast would have GSS = 0; a perfect forecast would have GSS
 = 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Hanssen-Kuipers Discriminant (H-K)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Called "HK" in CTS output (Table 4-5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
H-K is defined as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{H-K}={{n_{11}n_{00}-n_{10}n_{01}}
\backslash
over{(n_{11}+n_{01})(n_{10}+n_{00})}}.$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
More simply, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
hbox{H-K}=
\backslash
hbox{POD}-
\backslash
hbox{POFD}.$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
H-K is also known as the True Skill Statistic (TSS) and less commonly (although
 perhaps more properly) as the Peirce Skill Score.
 H-K measures the ability of the forecast to discriminate between (or correctly
 classify) events and non-events.
 H-K values range between -1 and 1.
 A value of 0 indicates no skill; a perfect forecast would have H-K = 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Heidke Skill Score (HSS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Called "HSS" in CTS output (Table 4-5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
HSS is a skill score based on Accuracy, where the Accuracy is corrected
 by the number of correct forecasts that would be expected by chance.
 In particular,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{HSS}=
\backslash
displaystyle{{{n_{11}+n_{00}-C_2}
\backslash
over{T-C_2}}},$$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

