\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Reliability 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
A component of the Brier score.
 Reliability measures the average difference between forecast probability
 and average observed frequency.
 Ideally, this measure should be zero as larger numbers indicate larger
 differences.
 For example, on occasions when rain is forecast with 50% probability, it
 should actually rain half the time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{Reliability}=
\backslash
frac{1}{T}
\backslash
sum{n_i(p_i-
\backslash
overline o_i)^2}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Resolution 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
A component of the Brier score that measures how well forecasts divide events
 into subsets with different outcomes.
 Larger values of resolution are best since it is desirable for event frequencie
s in the subsets to be different than the overall event frequency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{Resolution}=
\backslash
frac{1}{T}n_{i.}(
\backslash
overline o_i-
\backslash
overline o)^2$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Uncertainty 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
A component of the Brier score.
 For probabilistic forecasts, uncertainty is a function only of the frequency
 of the event.
 It does not depend on the forecasts, thus there is no ideal or better value.
 Note that uncertainty is equivalent to the variance of the event occurrence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hbox{Uncertainty}=
\backslash
frac{n_{.1}}{T}(1-
\backslash
frac{n_{.1}}{T})$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Brier score 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
The Brier score is the mean squared probability error.
 In MET, the Brier Score (BS) is calculated from the 
\series bold
nx2
\series default
 contingency table via the following equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$BS={1 
\backslash
over T}
\backslash
sum_{i=1}^K 
\backslash
left[ n_{i1} (1 - p_i)^2 + n_{i0} 
\backslash
, p_i^2 
\backslash
right]$$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation you will most often see in references uses the individual probabili
ty forecasts (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

) and the corresponding observations (
\series bold
o
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $_{i}$
\end_inset

), and is given as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$BS=
\backslash
frac{1}{T}
\backslash
sum(p_i-o_i)^2$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This equation is equivalent when the midpoints of the binned probability
 values are used as the 
\series bold
p
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
i
\end_layout

\end_inset


\series default
 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
BS can be partitioned into three terms: (1) reliability, (2) resolution,
 and (3) uncertainty (Murphy, 1973).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$BS=
\backslash
frac{1}{T}
\backslash
sum_i(p_i-o_i)^2=
\backslash
frac{1}{T}
\backslash
sum n_{i.}(p_i-
\backslash
overline o_i)^2-
\backslash
